snippet.textDisplay: Just to let you know about the 3060 "hack." I suspect this is something Nvidia is intentionally experimenting with. Why? Because it only works on one card, it has to plugged into the 1st 16x slot. It will not work on a riser. So it still won't work on a multi card rig but a one card gaming PC, it works just fine. It would make sense for Nvidia to allow mining for their gaming customers while still blocking it for farms.

snippet.textDisplay:
Does a mining card need the tensor or ray tracing cores? Dealing with the contention between miners and gamers seems like it needs dedicated hardware that matches the hash rates of an equivalent gaming GPU for a lower price. 
One way to potentially deal with the e-waste issue could be to allow those CUDA cores to get teamed up with the ones on the GPU somehow. I think all the building blocks are there but it would take pressure for Nvidia to do the engineering to make it work reasonably well. But none of those things make any sense to explore in the current market.
snippet.textOriginal:
